    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Facebook Groups</strong> are community spaces on Meta's platform where people with shared interests gather to post, comment, and connect around specific topics. Groups can be public, private, or hidden, and range from local neighborhood communities to global professional networks. Unlike Facebook Pages (brand-to-audience broadcasting), Groups facilitate member-driven two-way conversations.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Monthly active users</div>
            <div class="tms-value">1.8 billion (Meta, 2024)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Social Media</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Organic reach advantage</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Higher than Pages</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Beginner</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Facebook Pages have seen organic reach collapse to below 5% over the last decade. Facebook Groups operate differently: the algorithm prioritizes group content in members' feeds because it treats group activity as personal — not promotional. For businesses that can build genuine community, Groups represent one of the last high-organic-reach channels on the platform.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What are Facebook Groups?</h2>
        <p>Facebook Groups are dedicated spaces within Meta's platform where members with shared interests or goals interact through posts, comments, polls, events, and files. Each group has an admin team that sets rules, approves members, and moderates content.</p>
        <p>Groups differ from Facebook Pages in a fundamental way:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Facebook Page:</strong> A brand broadcasts content to followers. Reach is mostly paid. Conversation flows one direction.</li>
          <li><strong>Facebook Group:</strong> Members post to each other. The brand facilitates rather than broadcasts. Conversation flows in all directions.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Groups come in three privacy levels:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Public:</strong> Anyone can see the group, its members, and all posts. Searchable and fully indexable.</li>
          <li><strong>Private:</strong> The group is discoverable in search, but content is only visible to members. Most common for brand communities.</li>
          <li><strong>Hidden:</strong> Invisible in search. Members can only join via direct invitation from an existing member or admin.</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Meta data on Group engagement</div>
          <p>According to Meta, <strong>1.8 billion people use Facebook Groups every month</strong>. Group content receives significantly higher organic reach than Page content because Facebook's algorithm classifies group interactions as personal social activity — the same category as messages between friends — rather than brand content competing for News Feed space.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why Facebook Groups matter for businesses</h2>
        <p>Groups serve three commercial functions that standard social media marketing cannot replicate:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Organic reach at scale.</strong> While brand Page posts reach less than 5% of followers organically, group posts regularly reach 20-40% of members — because the algorithm treats group activity as social, not promotional. For businesses that have lost organic reach on Pages, Groups provide a credible alternative.</li>
          <li><strong>Direct customer relationships without competing for attention.</strong> In a group, your brand has a direct line to members who opted in specifically. You're not competing with their friends' holiday photos for News Feed space — the group is a dedicated channel.</li>
          <li><strong>User-generated content factory.</strong> Active groups produce questions, testimonials, use-case discussions, and complaints that give brands real-time product feedback and organic content. Members answering each other's questions — citing your product positively — is more persuasive than any ad.</li>
          <li><strong>Lead generation mechanism.</strong> When people request to join a group, admins can add membership questions — effectively a lead capture form for warm prospects who actively sought engagement with your brand's topic area.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How to build and run a Facebook Group for business</h2>
        <p>A business Facebook Group strategy has three phases:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Create around a topic, not a brand.</strong> Groups named after the brand ("Acme Software Users") attract a narrower audience than groups named around the problem or interest ("Small Business Automation Tips"). Broader topic framing attracts a larger potential member base, including people who discover the group before discovering the brand.</li>
          <li><strong>Moderate and engage consistently.</strong> Set clear group rules (no spam, no self-promotion without permission, stay on topic). Post a weekly discussion prompt. Respond to every member question within 24 hours for the first six months. Feature member posts in the weekly digest. Consistency in the first 90 days determines whether a group becomes self-sustaining.</li>
          <li><strong>Drive value that justifies membership.</strong> The group must give members something they cannot get elsewhere: expert answers, early access, exclusive discounts, or community with people who share a niche interest. Groups that exist only to promote the brand's products empty out quickly. Groups that genuinely serve members grow through word-of-mouth.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="types">Facebook Group types for business</h2>

