        <h2 id="examples">Real Facebook Group examples for businesses</h2>

        <h3>1. Local real estate agent — topic community group</h3>
        <p>A real estate agent created "First-Time Homebuyers [City Name]" — a group providing weekly market updates, buying process tips, and open Q&A. The group grew to <strong>3,000 members</strong> over 18 months through community referrals and local Facebook search discovery. The agent closed <strong>8 deals annually</strong> directly traceable to group members or their referrals — at zero incremental ad spend.</p>

        <h3>2. B2B SaaS — customer community group</h3>
        <p>A project management software company built a private customer community where product users share workflow tips, request features, and help each other with questions. The group became the primary product feedback channel and reduced support ticket volume by <strong>20%</strong> as members answered each other's questions faster than the support team could.</p>

        <h3>3. Fitness studio — local community group</h3>
        <p>A boutique gym created a group for members with daily workout tips, nutrition posts, and weekly challenges. Non-members could join the group without buying a membership. The group served as a low-friction trial experience — members experienced the culture before committing to a subscription, improving trial-to-paid conversion by 30%.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Facebook Groups vs Facebook Pages — which to use</h2>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Facebook Groups</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Community conversation, member-driven</li>
              <li>High organic reach (algorithm treats as social)</li>
              <li>Direct relationship with engaged audience</li>
              <li>UGC and peer support generated by members</li>
              <li>Lead capture through membership questions</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Facebook Pages</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Brand broadcasting, one-to-many</li>
              <li>Low organic reach (under 5% of followers)</li>
              <li>Required for running Facebook ads</li>
              <li>Better for official brand presence and verification</li>
              <li>Public-facing — visible to non-followers</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 best practices for building a business Facebook Group</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Name the group around the member's interest, not your brand.</strong> "Social Media Marketing Tips" grows faster than "[Your Agency Name] Clients." Topic-first naming attracts organic discovery through Facebook search.</li>
          <li><strong>Add membership questions that capture lead data.</strong> Ask for email address as one of 3 membership questions. Members who fill this out are warm leads — they want in enough to provide their contact details.</li>
          <li><strong>Post a pinned welcome post and group rules immediately.</strong> New members read the pinned post first. Use it to set expectations, share the group's value proposition, and invite introductions.</li>
          <li><strong>Create a weekly content cadence.</strong> Monday motivation, Wednesday Q&A thread, Friday wins — predictable content builds the habit of checking the group. Admin abandonment is the #1 reason groups fail.</li>
          <li><strong>Feature member contributions.</strong> Highlight member posts in a weekly digest or "best of the week" post. Recognition drives more posting. Members who feel seen contribute more and stay longer.</li>
          <li><strong>Use polls to drive engagement and gather data.</strong> Polls get higher engagement than text posts and generate product insight. "What's your biggest challenge with [topic]?" is both engagement and market research.</li>
          <li><strong>Enforce rules consistently.</strong> Allow one spam post and you'll have twenty within a week. The group's quality is only as good as its moderation. Protect the community experience — it's the product you're delivering.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — treating the group as a broadcasting channel</div>
          <p>Businesses that join or create Facebook Groups only to post promotional content drive members away instantly. Groups with more than 20% promotional content from the admin lose members faster than they add them. The rule of thumb: 80% of content should serve the community's interests, 20% can serve the business's interests. If the ratio flips, the group fails.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common Facebook Group mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Creating a group without a moderation plan</strong> — unmoderated groups fill with spam within weeks; name the admin team before launch.</li>
          <li><strong>Naming the group after the brand instead of the topic</strong> — limits discovery and gives potential members no reason to join before they know the brand.</li>
          <li><strong>Not adding membership questions</strong> — missing the highest-quality lead capture moment in the entire group funnel.</li>
          <li><strong>Inconsistent posting cadence</strong> — dormant groups decay; members disengage and the algorithm stops showing group content in their feeds.</li>
          <li><strong>Posting only promotional content</strong> — the fastest way to kill engagement and trigger member requests to leave.</li>
          <li><strong>Not connecting group activity to business metrics</strong> — track which members became customers, how many support tickets the group deflected, and what product feedback changed roadmap decisions.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
